Epidemic typhus serves as the prototype disease in the group and has more severe clinical manifestations.

  • Fever (prolonged; about 2 weeks if untreated), headache, fatigue
  • Rash - a small, painless, gradually enlarging papule, which leads to an area of central necrosis and is followed by eschar formation.
  • A more widespread macular / maculopapular rash may also be seen. Source in about 50% of patients.
    • it is non pruritic, starts on the abdomen and spreads outwards.
  • The features above don't seem life threatening but
    • Pneumonitis or encephalitis, Central nervous system (CNS), pulmonary, or cardiac involvement, Rarely, acute renal failure, shock, and disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC) can occur!
  • may have splenomegaly, and hepatomegaly. Source
  • In #pregnancy , scrub typhus frequently leads to spontaneous abortions.Source <- in pregnancy, patients are treated with azithromycin, not doxycycline.

Physiologic haematologic changes in pregnancy

  • Haemoglobin

  • iron deficiency is frequent.

  • Folate deficiency:

  • Vitamin B12 levels fall slightly in pregnancy but there is no deficiency. Levels but recover post partum.

  • Platelet counts fall by 10% of baseline.

    • Probably due to platelet sequestration in splenic and placental circulation.
    • Platelet counts drop progressively throughout pregnancy and rise after delivery.
    • But counts still remain within the normal range in uncomplicated pregnancies.
    • Counts within 150,000 to 100,000 range are likely to be [[#Incidental thrombocytopaenia of pregnancy]].
    • However, this physiological thrombocytopaenia can be severe in 7% of pregnant women. Should look for other causes if especially if Plt count is < 100,000.
    • See [[#Thrombocytopaenia in pregnancy]] below

  • Coagulation

Thrombocytopaenia in pregnancy

  • Defined as platelets < 150,000.
  • There can be many causes. Commonest is incidental thrombocytopaenia of pregnancy.
  • 75% - the cause is idiopathic and with mild thrombocytopaenia. - [[#Incidental thrombocytopaenia of pregnancy]]
  • 21% - secondary to hypertensive disorder
  • 4% - immune thrombocytopaenic purpura.

Incidental thrombocytopaenia of pregnancy

  • Also called gestational thrombocytopaenia (GT)
  • Diagnosis of exclusion
  • Most common at delivery.
  • Count is greater than 100k. (usually between 150k to 100k)
  • No other bleeding manifestations will be seen.
  • Recovers in 6 weeks.
  • No treatment needed.

Other causes to consider

  • ITP
  • [[Hypertension in pregnancy|Hypertensive disorders of pregnancy]]
  • DIC
  • [[Hypertension in pregnancy#Acute fatty liver of pregnancy|Acute fatty liver of pregnancy]]
  • Thrombotic microangiopathy - TTP, HUS
  • Viral infection - Dengue

Iron FESO4 / sulphate overdose

#2021GM-JUL/Q13

[!INFO] Iron preparations compositions:

  • Ferrous fumarate (33% elemental iron)
  • Ferrous sulfate (20% elemental iron)
  • Ferrous gluconate (12% elemental iron)

  • Toxic dose: <20mg - no problems; 20-60 - mild to moderate, >60mg - severe symptoms.

  • Potentially fatal in preschool aged children.

  • Iron is toxic to GI system, cardiovascular system and CNS.

    • interferes with oxidative phosphorylation, causing metabolic acidosis.
    • Generates free radicals, acts as oxidiser, forms FeOH and H+

  • Cellular toxicity occurs within hours! -> symptoms occur within 6 hours of ingestion.

  • Liver toxicity occurs within days.

  • GI tract and stomach fibrosis -> Weeks

[!INFO] Iron toxicity occurs in 5 stages

  • Severity of the first stage (6h) is indicative of the prognosis. If first stage is mild, severe symptoms later are unlikely.
  • 6 - 48 hours there is a latent period with apparent impovement.- Don't be fooled.

Investigations:

  • Abdominal X ray will show iron tablets (but not liquid preprations)
  • So Serum iron, pH, electrolytes too look for signs of toxicity. (9Serum iron levels > 350 mcg/dL at 3 to 5 hours)
  • ABG will show HAGMA. (high anion gap)

Management:

  • Activated charcoal isn't effective
  • Vomiting is clears GI contents more effectively than lavage so it's not indicated.
  • Whole bowel irrigation with Polyethylene glycol is done.
  • For severe toxicity, IV deferoxamine (aka desferrioxamine)

Methanol poisoning

  • "wood alcohol"; used as an organic solvent.
  • Methanol itself is only weakly toxic.
  • Formic acid is the toxic metabolite. (as little at 30ml of methanol can be significantly toxic needing dialysis)
  • Formic acid causes HAGMA. (severity and duration of acidosis corelate with mortality)
  • Absorption is rapid (within 10 minutes of ingestion) and elimination is zero order. Source
    -

Presentation:

  • Symptoms occur 12 - 24 hours after ingestion
  • Symptoms are delayed with co-ingestion of ethanol because there is competitive inhibitions.
  • There is a latent period followed by symptoms similar to ethanol intoxication with ataxia, disinhibition.
  • There is an "osmolar gap": a difference between calculated osmolality and actual osmolality of blood.
    • Osmolality is calculated as = 2(Na) + (glucose/18) + (BUN/2.8)
    • presumably, formic acid increases osmolality while not being included in this equation -> causes osmolar gap.
    • Osmolar gap > 25 mOsm/Kg is indication to start treatment.Sourc
  • Nausea, vomiting, and abdominal pain subsequently ensue,
  • followed by central nervous system (CNS) depression and hyperventilation as metabolic acidosis occurs. Ocular symptoms associated with retinal toxicity are often evident in the form of blurry vision, decreased visual acuity, photophobia, and â€œhalo vision.â€
  • These symptoms are associated with physical exam findings that may include papilloedema, optic disc hyperemia, and pupillary defects on fundoscopic evaluation.

Management:

  • Antidotes: Ethanol and fomepizole.
    • Fomepizole is an inhibitor of alcohol dehydrogenase used as an antidote in confirmed or suspected methanol or ethylene glycol poisoning but it's expensive and not widely available.
    • The afinity for alcohol dehydrogenase for ethanol (and fomepizole) is much higher than for methanol.
  • Dialysis can remove methanol and formic acid.
    • Indications: (1) greater than 30mL of methanol ingested, (2) serum methanol level greater than 20 mg/dL, (3) observation of visual complications, and (4) no improvement in acidosis despite repeated sodium bicarbonate infusions.

Complications:

  • Vision loss due to occular toxicity of methanol. Changes are visible fundoscopically within hours. Can be prevented with antidotes or dialysis. Damage is mainly to the optic nerve and not the retina. Visual toxicity initially presents as flashes of light and blurring and scotoma. Can occur even with inhalation of methanol.
  • Movement disorders: Parkinsonian motor impairment is seen in survivors; probably due to formic acid toxicity to the putamen. Onset if several weeks after the toxic dose.

Ethylene glycol poisoning

  • Ethylene glycol is used to elevate the boiling point and lower the freezing point of radiator fluid.
  • Sweet tasting.
  • Mechanism:
  • Like ethyl alcohol and methanol, ethylene glycol is metabolized by ADH. In this step it forms glycoaldehyde. Through interaction with aldehyde dehydrogenase, ethylene glycol is then metabolized to glycolic acid (GA), which accumulates and can cause a profound metabolic acidosis. This glycolic acid is eventually converted into glyoxylic acid, and then into the highly toxic oxalate or the safer glutamate or Î±-ketoadipic acid metabolites.
  • Symptoms :
    • 30 mins to 12 hours : Ethanol like effects on the CNS.
    • 12 to 48 hours: metabolite (glycolic acid) produces severe high anion gap metabolic acidosis. Calcium oxalate crystals become deposited in brain, lungs kidneys and heart.
    • 24 to 72 hours, acute kidney injury can result from the direct renal toxic effects of the ethylene glycol metabolite calcium oxylate monohydrate.
  • Treatment:
    • Initial emergency department treatment includes infusion of crystalloids to enhance renal clearance of the toxic metabolites. Ethyl alcohol (ethanol) has traditionally been used for antidotal treatment, but it has largely been supplanted by fomepizole in the United States.

Polymyositis and dermatomyositis

#2021GM-JUL/Q15

From MCQ discussion:

[!INFO]

Q 11: Dermatomyositis

Ragged cucitles are seen; heliotrope rash, nail fold telangiectasia
Shawl sign
Gottron's papules
Calcinosis is a feature - more proximal distribution. More common in juvenile dermatomyositis.
A large percentage (30 - 40%) is associated with malignancy!
Commoner in females. Toxoplasmosis can cause a similar syndrome.

  • Occurs at all ages; aetiology unknown but may involve coxsackie / rubella viruses.
  • Women >> men by 3:1
  • Polymyositis:
    • Acute or subacute onset of proximal muscle weakness associated with constitutional symptoms. Laryngeal and respiratory muscles are affected without treatment.
  • Dermatomyositis:
    • Also commoner in women
    • Most specific rash is the heliotrope rash but it's present only in a minority.
  • Antisynthetase syndrome
    • 20% of those with PM or DM have anti tRNA synthetase antibodies and are more likely to get pulmonary interstitial fibrosis, Raynaud's phenomenon, and "mechanic's hands".
    • Has a poor outcome.
    • Respiratory muscles are affected -> respiratory failure;
    • Oesophageal muscle involvement -> dysphagia.

[!INFO] DM and PM are strongly associated with malignancies
Association is particularly strong in the first 2 years after diagnosis.
Patient diagnosed with DM / PM needs to be thoroughly screened for malignancy.
Commonly associated malignancies are:

  • breast
  • ovarian
  • lung
  • and hematologic cancers,
  • as well as nasopharyngeal cancer in Asian populations. Source

Investigations:

  • creatine kinase, aminotransferases, LDH and aldolase are all raised.
  • ESR and CRP â†‘
  • ANA +, RF +, myositis specific antibodies. Antisynthetase antibodies.
  • EMG: spontaneous fibrillation potentials, polyphasic potentials and salvos of repetitive potentials on mechanical stimulation of the nerve.
  • Muscle biopsy: fibre necrosis and regeneration with lymphocytic infiltrate.

Treatment:

  • Mainstay of treatment is prednisilone, continued for at least 1 month after clinical and biochemical resolution of myositis.
  • Steroids must be weaned slowly.
  • Azathioprine, ciclosporin, cyclophosphamide and MMF are all used as steroid sparing agents.
  • IVIG in refractory cases.

Anticoagulation for prosthetic valves

Depends on the which valve is replaced, which type of mechanical valve is used and presence of other thromboembolic risk factors.

Risk factors here refer to:

  • History of thromboembolism,
  • hypercoagulability,
  • dysfunctional left ventricle, or atrial fibrillation.

So far, the only option for anticoagulation with mechanical heart valves is warfarin.

Source (more complicated version can be found on UpToDate)

[!INFO] How to remember
Aortic valve: 2-3 for 3 months and then 1.5 to 2.
Aortic valve with risk factor or mitral valve - 2.5 - 3.5.
